sols_latex:
To get our bounds of integration, we need to know where the intersection
points are. Also, from the graph, the top function changes, so we need
to find out exactly where this occurs, which is another point of
intersection. The intersections can be found by solving

\begin{align*}
4+\pi \sin x &= 4+2\pi-2x \\
x &= \pi - \frac{\pi}{2} \sin x
\end{align*}

This isn't easy to solve, but the graph shows three intersection points
which can be estimated then checked. It looks like the three
intersection points are $\displaystyle x = \pi/2, \pi, 3\pi/2$. At
$\displaystyle x = \pi/2$,

\begin{align*}
\pi - \frac{\pi}{2} \sin \frac{\pi}{2} = \pi - \frac{\pi}{2} \cdot 1 = \frac{\pi}{2}
\end{align*}

so this is a solution. At $\displaystyle x = \pi$,

\begin{align*}
\pi - \frac{\pi}{2} \sin \pi = \pi - \frac{\pi}{2} \cdot 0 = \pi
\end{align*}

so this is a solution. At $\displaystyle x = 3\pi/2$,

\begin{align*}
\pi - \frac{\pi}{2} \sin \frac{3\pi}{2} = \pi - \frac{\pi}{2} \cdot (-1) = \frac{3\pi}{2}
\end{align*}

so this is a solution. Then, the intersection points are indeed
$\displaystyle x = \pi/2, \pi, 3\pi/2$. Notice the top function on
$\displaystyle [\pi/2,\pi]$ is $\displaystyle 4+\pi \sin x$, whereas the
top function on $\displaystyle [\pi,3\pi/2]$ is
$\displaystyle 4+2\pi-2x$.

We have

\begin{align*}
A &= \int_{\pi/2}^{\pi} \left[(4+\pi \sin x) - (4+2\pi-2x)\right] \ dx \\
&\qquad + \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \left[(4+2\pi-2x)-(4+\pi \sin x)\right] \ dx \\
&= (-\pi \cos x - 2\pi x + x^2)\big|_{\pi/2}^{\pi} + (\pi\cos x+2\pi x-x^2)\big|_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \\
&= 2(\pi - \pi^2/4)
\end{align*}

